  |> I have been working on BipolarType since the early 1980s when I was diagnosed as
  =link_to 'bipolar', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bipolar_disorder', class: 'external'
  |<> at around the same time I learned about
  =link_to 'personality type', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Personality_type', class: 'external'
  | .
p
  |> The BipolarType theory asserts that &ldquo;being bipolar&rdquo; is genetic, and causes the individual to experience a more pronounced
  =link_to 'cycle', cycle_path
  |> , but that different people have different
  =link_to 'natures', natures_path
  | , which affects not only how their illnesses present, but the treatments they need. I got my bipolar genes from my mother, but my symptoms were so different from hers that it was years before I was properly diagnosed — even though we knew that bipolar disorder runs in our family — and the treatments that worked for her did not work for me.

p
  |> The BipolarType theory further asserts that if you know what your
  =link_to 'BipolarType', types_path
  |< is, you will know what behaviors to focus on
  em<> wherever
  | you are in the cycle (manic, depressed, or mixed state). That is, the BipolarType provides a list of four behaviors that you can always do, that you always <em>enjoy</em> doing, and that are neither unhealthy nor unbalancing.
p
  |> The
  =link_to 'theory', theory_path
  |<> is scientific (it is
  =link_to 'falsifiable', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Falsifiability', class: 'external'
  | )
  |< but it has not been validated by the psychiatric, psychological, or type communities.
p
  |> I am sharing it on the web because it helps
  =link_to 'me', my_path
  | . I hope that you will find it useful or at least interesting.
